  "topic": "What is stereotype threat in STEM? Should we address it? And how?",
  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is when people feel anxious or underperform because they're worried about confirming negative stereotypes about their group, like women or minorities being less capable in science or math. As a 21-year-old hairdresser from Bari, I see this in my own way—I work with diverse clients and hear stories about how expectations can hold people back. Even though I'm not in STEM, I get it because I've faced my own stereotypes, like people thinking hairdressers aren't smart or serious, which can be depressing when you're already feeling low. We should definitely address it because it's unfair and wastes talent. In my job, I see how confidence matters; if someone feels judged, they might not try new styles or speak up. Similarly, in STEM, if bright minds are scared off by stereotypes, we lose out on innovation and progress. To fix it, we need to create supportive environments. Schools and workplaces should promote diversity and highlight success stories from all backgrounds, like showcasing women engineers or minority scientists. Mentorship programs could help, where experienced professionals guide newcomers, just like I learn from senior stylists. Also, raising awareness through education—maybe in vocational training like mine—can teach people about these biases. Personally, as someone with high openness and extraversion, I believe in talking openly about these issues, even if my agreeableness is low and I don't always sugarcoat things. We can use social media wisely, though I'm not on it much, to spread positive messages. Ultimately, addressing stereotype threat is about fairness and unlocking potential, which benefits everyone, whether in STEM or a salon in Bari.",
